Diane von Furstenberg is my fave all time designer considering I'm no fashionista chica. Lucy the Time Traveling Chihuahua visits her here in the 1970's. Wish to meet DVF someday. Love her style late 60's - 70's best. Her dresses has signature V-shape theme. She took the most modest details of 1940's dress fashion - and turned them into independent, outspoken revolution. Sexy, sassy, and driven. Nothing sad, pathetic or desperate about her style. Her dresses make **ALL** sized women gorgeous. Ironically she comes from the "anorexia snort cocaine size 0" era of fashion. But I wished her "factory" would embrace the Big Girls Club as we lose weight - in her line. Love pics of her at Studio 54 and the famous Andy Warhol polaroids. "The vast majority of the women in my life are incredibly strong. My grandmother survived 8 different types of cancer after being exposed to radiation in Japan during WWII. My mother is an unbelievably intelligent lawyer who never settles for less-than-perfect work. My sister works at a nonprofit fighting homelessness in New York City and around the country. My friends have accomplishments ranging from obtaining representation as a screenwriter in Hollywood to managing dozens of people to starting Italian Collective.  This has been by far the most influential thing in my life. I have never for a second doubted what we as women could accomplish; that I could prove anyone wrong when they underestimate me; that the women I know who inspire me will inspire others and affect change.  Italian Collective represents so much of what feminism means to me. It's a women-run company for women. Wearing it makes me feel like I can do anything. And seeing its success makes me so, so proud." Not only was this a delicious dinner, but it was an extremely unique experience for us as well.  We don't know what sushi in Japan tastes like, but we think this would come pretty close! Just refinished this dresser I made last year. Made from Claro walnut and steel this thing has enough character to go around. The material I got from @moorenewtonhardwoods. Apparently the tree was felled some time ago and this wood was salvaged from a barn that was being demoed. It's always nice to use material that has a history, although every piece of wood has a history, some stories are better than others. There are even some bullets imbedded in a couple of the slab. Pretty cool. The finish is about 10 coats of wipe on poly followed by wax. The puppy will be on it's way to Atlanta next week. @nnnnolannnn I hope you're ready!!

Vertical lines play across the horizontal frame creating a pattern and adding to the perception of depth.  ICM (interntional camera motion) takes an ordinary scene and makes it extraordinary.  What I had learned:  Camera motion can distill elements to just whatâ€™s essential. So why is it that ex-pat's done move here? Reykjavik has the mountain chill of Colorado,  the mesa-like surfaces of Utah or Arizona, combined with the hills of San Francisco, and the small coastal bodegas of Northern California. The people are stylish, the architecture utilizes clean lines, bright colours, and the city is fairly clean. I really can't wait to read the Haldor Laxness book I bought a while back. I already can't wait to come back and give it a real go, rather than just the 4 or so hours I've had. A week next time would be all the better. Also, I'd like to work on the language a little next time before I come. Thank you, Reykjavik. Now to spend the night in your country's airport haha.

#HA recovery update: I feel happier.  ##  It isn't always fun. There are days when I really want to workout. Surprisingly, I haven't missed super high intensity, fast and burning workouts, but I do miss lifting kettlebells and other heavy stuff. I'm actually craving it.  ##  However, I've decided to hold off because there are so many women before me who have recovered from #HA by exercising minimally, eating more, restingâ€“both their body and mind, and gaining weight. Of course all of us hope this journey is not endless! (It won't). ##  But meanwhile, I'm not going to waste my time on stressing and hating everything about #HA. It's a lesson that came to my way for some reason.  ##  Besides, even though working out is very important part of my life and it always will be, there are many other things in life to enjoy too. This weekend, I read a great book, had a nice walk in my favorite city #sanfrancisco, had a tasty dinner and wine @causwells, and I'm finally getting over 5-day long cold. Cheers to all that and staying positive.  ##  #hypothalamicamenorrhea #amenorrhea #recovery #amenorrhearecovery #getyourperiodback #HA #HArecovery #noperiod #hypothalamicamenorrhearecovery #infertility  #femaleathletetriad #ttc #fatsyndrome #mindset #personaltrainer

In my late teens I struggled with a serious life threatening eating disorder. I was plagued by fear and lived in my own personal prison. The only way out was to face what I had avoided looking at for many years.  I'm grateful for that resilient young lady within who paved the way for me to live a much more empowered and purpose driven life today.  The inner work is never done, I continue to see where my fears unconsciously run the show. Whether it's career, financial, relationships, physical health - if I'm avoiding something in my life it becomes the pausing point.. When my desire to create something new for myself is strong enough I've found I'll do what it takes to face my fear.  Life Activation is an amazing session I offer in person that helps you move past your fears more gracefully and shed perceived limitations. Jackie (2016) Cast: Natalie Portman, Caspar Phillipson, Peter Sarsgaard, Greta Gerwig, Billy Crudup. Drama/Biography / rated R Directed by Pablo LarraÃ­n After the assassination of John F. Kennedy, First Lady Jackie Kennedy must confront the world and life without her husband. She faces grief, becoming a single parent, and planning a funeral worthy enough for the President of the United States and one the American people will never forget. Without a doubt, Natalie Portmanâ€™s portrayal of Jackie Kennedy was the absolute best part of the film. She puts on a powerhouse performance, one that was so full of emotion, and one that was worthy of the Academy Award this year. It may be her best performance yet. She embraces mannerisms, hand gestures, voice, and postures that are not her own incredibly well. The story offers insight into Jackieâ€™s mind and how she reacted to her husbandâ€™s assassination just minutes after. There is a powerful scene where she looks in the mirror just after the tragedy. It was a bone-chilling scene and quite possibly one of the best from the film but see it for yourself. The film is incredibly intimate; the camera staying close to faces throughout. There are multiple timelines at once, which somehow helped describe the complexity of Jackieâ€™s thoughts and her life after the tragedy. And in the end the subject matter falls heavy on the viewer and almost wears out the mind. But even so, Jackieâ€™s story stays with you and teaches something about how to take on the world in a time of loss. This is the Kung Pao Chicken from Cafe Colma inside of Lucky Chances Casino in Colma. Located just a few minutes south of San Francisco, Lucky Chances is the place to play if you're planning a weekend getaway to visit The City. With all that San Francisco has to offer, Lucky Chances is the nearest cardroom. Besides their 60 gaming tables, Lucky Chances' Cafe Colma also offers an impressive Asian menu, including authentic Filipino Cuisine. I settled on a standard, entry-level meal- the Kung Pao Chicken. While not considered a Filipino dish per se, it's a simple dish that is one of my favorites and it's served at most Asian restaurants throughout NorCal. I make a point to try the Kung Pao Chicken at many of my regular stops. Its a good way for me to start measuring the menu. For the record, I thought it had an excellent blend of spicy-sweet that mixed very well with the boatload of peanuts poured over the top. For me, the key to good Kung Pao is that it be spicy- but not too spicy....and you can't have enough peanuts. This dish satisfied on both counts. Beside it time to step aside and let other cosplayer be on the board. This year 2017 brought so much #nostagia as the first year I gotten into cosplay. I will compare event and talk about it in the end of the year picture and possibility a video. I had fun last year because one of my bestie Ashi was involved without her I kind of miss her being there and going home together  because every cosplayer friends I seen is at different stage of their  life. I want my life to be meaningful so next year I might go wearing a #Yukata and wait for the food or travel whatever happens, happen. I want to put my energy in something else.
